Introduction¶

In order to make money, insurance companies need to collect more in premiums than it spends on medical care to its beneficiaries. Every insurer makes a significant portion of its revenue by underwriting, which is basically charging a fee (called a premium) for taking on financial risk.

A great deal of time and money is invested to employ statistical and mathematical models to evaluate and mitigate the financial risk involved in different scenarios.

Therefore it is in the interest in the insurer to have data on insurance premiums and have models they can rely on to create the best contract.

The Data¶

The data comes from the book Machine Learning with R by Brett Lantz published by Packt Publishing. It is a simulated data set using hypothetical medical expenses. The data was gleamed from demographic statistics from the US Census Bureau for patients in the United States.

  • Since the data was already processed before being published, there are no missing values and all the data types are correct. There are 1338 observations and 7 variables. Here is a quick rundown of each variable and their context:
  • age: An integer value indicating the age of the beneficiary.
  • sex: The policy holders gender.
  • bmi: The Body Mass index of the beneficiary. It's a measure of how overweight or underweight a person is relative to their height. The formula for BMI (English Formula) is equal to $\frac{Weight (lbs)}{[Height (in)]^2} * 703$
  • children: The number of children/dependents covered by the insurance plan.
  • smoker: A categorical variable that contains the classes "yes" or "no" that indicate whether the insured regularly smokes tabacco.
  • region: The beneficiary's place of residence within the United States divided into four geographic regions: northeast, southeast, southwest, or northwest.
  • expenses: The medical costs each person charged to the insurance plan for the year.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In [122]:
app1 = dash.Dash(name='Age Distribution')
buffer = io.StringIO()

# Plot itself
fig1 = go.Figure(data=[go.Histogram(x=data['age'],
                                   marker=dict(
                                       line=dict(color='black', width=2)  # Dark borders with width of 2
                                   ))])
fig1.update_layout(title="Distribution of Age (Grouped Age Bin,Count)",
                  xaxis_title="Age",
                  yaxis_title="Count")

fig1.update_xaxes(fixedrange=True)
fig1.update_yaxes(fixedrange=True)

# Interactivity backend
fig1.write_html(buffer)
html_bytes = buffer.getvalue().encode()
encoded = base64.b64encode(html_bytes).decode()

app1.layout = html.Div([
    dcc.Graph(id="graph1", figure=fig1),
    html.A(
        href="data:text/html;base64," + encoded,
        download="plotly_graph.html"
    )
])

app1.run_server(port=8050, debug=False)
  • We immediately observe that most of the age groups are about equally represented. However, the 18-19 age group accounts for more than double of any other age group in this dataset. Why is this the case?
  • In the U.S, 18 is the legal age of adulthood (although this can vary from state to state). The Affordable Care Act allows individuals to buy health insurance as young as 18. This is also the age where someone may get their first job and leave their parent or gaurdians plan to enroll in an employers health plan. These resasons may explain the large representation of 18-19 year olds

  • Within this population BMI follows a near Normal Distribution. BMI is a continous variable that is naturally occuring and can be measured. Therefore, Normal-esque behavior is to be expected.
  • The average BMI is 30.66 with a standard deviation of 6.09

In [171]:
sns.pairplot(data)
plt.title("Pairplot of Numeric Variables")
plt.show()
  • We don't see any massive correlation with the expenses label. This means while there isn't a linear relationship with expenses and the other numeric variables, features may still provide predictive power if combined with other features. (Think: interaction terms in Polynomial Regression)

  • Another intersting finding is the pairplot, particularly the scatter plot between age and expenses. It looks like age is not telling at all of what expense may be. However, there is clearly some interesting grouping going on which may explain a hidden sub population. But why 3 and what are they grouping on?

  • We see further clustering in the scatterplot between bmi and expenses.

  • There may potentially be multimodal behavior happening in the distribution of expenses. Looks like theres 3 groups again. This might indicate the groups are based light,moderate, and sever medical conditions that cost more. A more sever case tends to be rare and more expensive.
